 to estimate the difficulty of knowledge units and identify prerequisite relationships without historical data is a significant advancement in adaptive learning technologies. [Data: Entities (19, 20), Relationships (16)]\n\n## Comparative analysis of Botswana's capital with other capitals\n\nThe project involving Botswana's capital and LLMs extends to comparing it with other capitals, including Cashion, for various criteria. This comparative analysis aims to draw insights and best practices from different urban environments to inform development strategies. Such an approach not only broadens the scope of the project but also enhances its applicability and relevance to Botswana's urban development objectives. [Data: Entities (31, 33), Relationships (30)]\n\n## The cold problem study's contribution to understanding the cold start issue\n\nThe study titled COLD_PROBLEM addresses the cold start problem, focusing on estimating the difficulty of knowledge units without historical data. This research contributes to a deeper understanding of the challenges and potential solutions in adaptive learning systems, complementing the efforts of LLMs in this domain. The study's insights into the cold start problem are invaluable for the ongoing development of more effective and personalized educational technologies. [Data: Entities (36, 20), Relationships (40)]	7.5	The impact severity rating is relatively high due to the significant potential of LLMs to revolutionize both educational systems and urban development planning.	[{"explanation": "Botswana is leveraging LLMs to analyze its capital's geographical, political, and social criteria in comparison with other African capitals. This innovative approach aims at identifying and proposing development projects, showcasing the potential of AI in enhancing urban planning and development strategies. The collaboration between Botswana and LLMs signifies a pioneering step towards integrating advanced technology in governmental planning pro